{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1548"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1548"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.15,0.24,0.24,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53944"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1548"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-12-16T22:04:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T11:16:54+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-07-08T13:00:57+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 17:49:53"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1548"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"738"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2759"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44053"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39415"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53944"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a history of a syncopal event. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. An electrocardiogram is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the electrocardiogram findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right bundle branch block","Left bundle branch block","First degree atrioventricular block","Bifascicular block","Trifascicular block"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe electrocardiogram shows a \u003Cstrong\u003Eright bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E (rsR\u0027 pattern in V1-V2), left axis deviation (positive QRS in lead I, negative QRS in leads II, III, aVF), and a prolonged PR interval consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst degree atrioventricular block\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of these three findings is referred to as \u003Cstrong\u003Etrifascicular block\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBifascicular block\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as right bundle branch block plus either left or right axis deviation, without a prolonged PR interval. Anatomically, this represents conduction block in two of the three fascicles of the His-Purkinje system (right bundle branch, left anterior fascicle, left posterior fascicle).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of bifascicular block plus either first degree or second degree atrioventricular block is referred to as \u003Cstrong\u003Etrifascicular block\u003C/strong\u003E. Anatomically, this represents impaired conduction in all three fascicles, although complete block may not be present in all three simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E is not seen on this ECG. Further evaluation with echocardiography and ambulatory ECG monitoring is warranted to assess for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trifascicular block can be present in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.","Trifascicular block is defined as bifascicular block plus either first degree or second degree AV block.","Bifascicular block is defined as right bundle branch block plus either left or right axis deviation."],"references":["Kliegman, Robert. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. Edition 21. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1548"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19823"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19823"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/466b84d1-f7cc-4c0e-b36e-3dcac070b320.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/466b84d1-f7cc-4c0e-b36e-3dcac070b320.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1444,"height":695}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T11:25:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T11:25:56+09:30","number":12,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1548"}},"content":{